In this paper, our intention is to present an XML engine defined to model and query multimodal concurrent annotated data. This work stands in the context of the OTIM (Tools for Multimodal Annotation) project which aims at developing conventions and tools for multimodal annotation of a large conversational French speech corpus (
http://aune.lpl.univ-aix.fr/~otim/) [
]. This interdisciplinary project is funded by the French ANR agency; it groups together Social Science and Computer Science researchers. Within OTIM, our objective is to provide linguists with a unique framework to encode and manipulate numerous linguistic domains: morpho-syntax, prosody, phonetics, disfluencies, discourse, gesture and posture [
]. For that, it has to be possible to bring together and align all the different pieces of information
(called annotations) associated to a corpus.

            	  Main proposals are usually classified in three categories [

][

].

Historical solutions which propose syntactic solutions for the representation of multiple hierarchies in the same text, like the CONCUR feature [
] of SGML or TEI specifications [
] (e.g. a flat representation or a main (hierarchical) structure and the use references (ID/IDREF) for the description of the other structures). These solutions make impossible querying by means of standards XML languages.

Proprietary graph based-model (and possible alternative syntax to XML) like LNML [
], TexMecs[
http://decentius.aksis.uib.no/mlcd/2003/Papers/texmecs.html], XCONCUR [
http://www.xconcur.org/], Annotation graphs [
] (coming from the linguistic domain coupled to specific extension of XPath) or MVDM [
]. They allow the concurrent markup relying on a granule of data common to all the structures. Nevertheless, hierarchical structures are easier to exploit compared to the graph structure which remain complex when a large number of structures exist. XML syntax for serialization or import/export XML syntax do not make easy their querying by XML standard languages.

            	Finally, the third category is XML compatible contributions; they generally propose
            extensions of XML data model (XDM) (

http://www.w3.org/XML/Datamodel.html) to consider a set of XML trees 
            	[

][

] or several trees sharing their leaves [

][

][

]
            	[

]. For querying, these proposals define extensions of XPath or XQuery in order to
            navigate between different structures either by extending the notion 
            	of step in XPath [

] or by adding new axis [

]. Another solution is to extend the semantics of the XQuery filter [

] 
            	to use as much as possible an unchanged  XQuery structure. Adding Allen’s relations
            [

] by means of function definitions enable to deal with overlapping [

][

].

Besides, some linguistic projects have a similar objective than OTIM, for instance NITE (
http://groups.inf.ed.ac.uk/nxt/), AGTK (
http://weblex.ens-lsh.fr/projects/xitools/logiciels/AGTK/agtk.htm), ATLAS [
], PAULA (
http://www.sfb632.uni-potsdam.de/~d1/paula/doc/), XStandoff [
]. These projects rely on graph-based model. They generally propose toolkits for multi-level annotation by means of libraries of data and annotation management. The multiplication of annotation schemes and coding formats is a severe limitation for interoperability. One solution consists in developing higher level approaches (e.g. GrAF [
]) or annotation graphs based formats on top of which conversion routines between tools can be developed (see the Atlas Interchange Format [
]). However, these experiments still remain very programmatic.

Within the project OTIM, linguists propose an encoding for annotating spoken language data, with the acoustic signal as well as its orthographic transcription. They have chosen to use Typed Feature Structures [
][
] (TFS) to represent in an unified view the knowledge and the information they need for annotation. TFS representation is usual for linguists: it aims at normalizing, sharing and exchanging annotation schemas between experts. Linguistic annotation tools rely on native and not often open formats which are not directly interoperable. TFS provides an abstract description using a high level formalism independent from coding languages and tools.

We currently work to propose a knowledge representation formalism which be an alternative to TFS: an ontological approach based on Description Logics [
] (DL) and on semantic web technologies for the development of a linguistic Knowledge-based Information System. We have already defined a linguistic ontology from the TFS provided
by linguists for prosody, phonetics, lexical and disfluency domains. An applicative framework is under development, it is based on semantic web proposals such as OWL DL (Ontology Web Language5) for the representation of this ontology and SPARQL [
] the querying language of semantic web for its manipulation.
